f405db928", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "1", "file_name": "undergradute_handbook.pdf", "file_path": "data/undergradute_handbook.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 423047, "creation_date": "2025-07-23", "last_modified_date": "2025-07-23", "source_type": "file", "page_count": 31, "edubot_metadata": {"document_id": "9af9d4ac-bfd1-420d-b3cf-de2fa40f2758", "date_uploaded": "2025-07-31T01:10:20.972861", "title": "2008 Handbook", "summary": "This handbook provides information for Computer Science and Engineering students at Obafemi Awolowo University, Ile-Ife. It covers departmental staff, university history, facilities, examination regulations, the degree program, and procedures for academic matters.  The handbook aims to guide students through their studies and advises them to consult their academic advisors for major decisions.", "source": {"organization": "Obafemi Awolowo University", "url": null, "authority_tier": 3, "reliability_score": 0.9}, "temporal": {"publication_date": "2008", "last_updated": "August 2014", "validity_period": "2008", "version": null}, "classification": {"education_level": ["tertiary"], "content_type": "handbook", "subject_areas": ["Computer Science", "Engineering", "Mathematics", "Economics"], "geographic_scope": "institutional", "institution_types": ["university"]}, "processing": {"extraction_method": "manual", "quality_score": 0.9, "human_verified": false, "last_reviewed": null, "last_modified": null}, "linguistic": {"primary_language": "english", "secondary_languages": [], "terminology_complexity": "intermediate"}, "search_optimization": {"keywords": ["Obafemi Awolowo University", "Ile-Ife", "Computer Science", "Engineering", "Handbook", "Students", "Undergraduate", "Postgraduate", "Degree Program", "Examination Regulations"], "synonyms": [], "common_queries": ["What are the admission requirements?", "What courses are offered?", "What are the examination rules?", "Who are the departmental staff?", "What are the university facilities?"]}}, "document_id": "9af9d4ac-bfd1-420d-b3cf-de2fa40f2758"}, "hash": "d933fc45506ac734a8fd41c2a518bf68ab50f9844152ae4b2e49ca35fa311e15", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "II MEASUREMENT OF PERFORMANCE\nPerformance in a course shall be measured in term of:\n(i) The results of prescribed theory and practical examination; \n(ii) Continuous assessment which shall constitute 40% of measured performance;\n(iii) Assessment of such essay, practical exercises and reports prescribed for each course;\n9. The Course Unit System and the Computation of Grade Point Average (CGPA) \nThe  Course  Unit  System  is  used  to  assess  student\u2019s  performance  in  the  Faculty  of \nTechnology. In the course unit system, students are expected to register for courses with  \nspecified  units.  The  result  at  the  end  of  each  academic  period  will  depend  on  their \nperformance in each of the courses. Courses with higher units will affect your performance  \nmore than courses with lower units. The maximum number of units you can register for in  \none academic semester is 24 while the minimum is 15. You will need special permission  \nfor units outside this range. Under the guidance of your Academic Part Adviser, you  \n\nshould select appropriate courses and register for them within the period stipulated by the  \nuniversity.\nIt  is  important  to  inform  your  Academic  Part  Adviser  of  any  course  you  are  having \noutstanding, if such information is available to you. Note that you may not register for a  \ncourse until you have passed all the pre-requisites for the course. Some courses also have  \nco-requisites, along with which thee course must be registered for. Failure to submit your  \nregistration materials to your Academic Part Adviser may lead to serious problems with  \nyour results. As a means of feedback to guide you on your academic performance, you  \nneed to understand how to compute your results. This is explained in the following section.\n\uf0a7 Definition of Important Abbreviations:\n Each course has a unit. A course is specified by a numerical value which states how much \nweight the course will carry in terms of work loads. A unit may be any of the following \nweekly activities:\no One hour of lecture (L)\no One hour of Tutorial (T)\no Three hours of Practical (P)\nThe unit of a course is coded as (L-T-P) meaning \u2013 Lecture, Tutorial and Practical hours. A \n3 unit course described as (2-1-0) implies that you are expected to do two hours of lecture,  \none hour of tutorial and no practical classes every week for one semester.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 13728, "end_char_idx": 16104, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c8561511-ca60-4250-87ce-3d02867e0890": {"__data__": {"id_": "c8561511-ca60-4250-87ce-3d02867e0890", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "1", "file_name": "undergradute_handbook.pdf", "file_path": "data/undergradute_handbook.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 423047, "creation_date": "2025-07-23", "last_modified_date": "2025-07-23", "source_type": "file", "page_count": 31, "edubot_metadata": {"document_id": "9af9d4ac-bfd1-420d-b3cf-de2fa40f2758", "date_uploaded": "2025-07-31T01:10:20.972861", "title": "2008 Handbook", "summary": "This handbook provides information for Computer Science and Engineering students at Obafemi Awolowo University, Ile-Ife. It covers departmental staff, university history, facilities, examination regulations, the degree program, and procedures for academic matters.  The handbook aims to guide students through their studies and advises them to consult their academic advisors for major decisions.", "source": {"organization": "Obafemi Awolowo University", "url": null, "authority_tier": 3, "reliability_score": 0.9}, "temporal": {"publication_